title: If CFI writing fails, print an error and continue.
body:
This restores the error handling from elf.rs from before
https://github.com/mozilla/dump_syms/pull/433 . That PR changed it to
an unwrap because the PDB code was using unwrap.

old elf.rs: https://github.com/mozilla/dump_syms/blob/de7cc440533b794f85ca4e1f10e26d918330140d/src/linux/elf.rs#L464-L466
old pdb.rs: https://github.com/mozilla/dump_syms/blob/de7cc440533b794f85ca4e1f10e26d918330140d/src/windows/pdb.rs#L254

We encounter this error for libmozavutil.so on certain Linux debug builds,
see https://bugzilla.mozilla.org/show_bug.cgi?id=1783899#c6 .

title: Remove PDB code and use symbolic_debuginfo for all platforms
body:
Fixes #406.
Fixes #280.

This PR adds inline support for Windows.
It also removes 1500 lines of code at the same time.

I've ported the following features from the Windows code to the cross-platform code:

 - Some Windows path handling (used in the source file code)
 - Appending a dummy symbol based on the last known symbol
 - Adopting the FUNC name from the PUBLIC at the same address if the function name doesn't have parameter information
 - Decoding parameter size from "C decorated" symbol names, and assigning it to the function or public at that address
 - Generating synthetic functions from the PE object's exception info, if no PDB is available
 - Skipping public symbols for string and number constants
 - Already landed: setting the "multiple" flag if multiple publics or functions have the same address (PR #416)

I've also upstreamed the following changes to symbolic:

- Emit function parameters, by using a TypeFormatter (https://github.com/getsentry/symbolic/pull/426)
- Include functions from SeparatedCode symbols (https://github.com/getsentry/symbolic/pull/622)
- Include symbols which are not marked as functions, as long as they're from an executable section (https://github.com/getsentry/symbolic/pull/641)
- Allow detecting C decorated functions by not stripping underscores (https://github.com/getsentry/symbolic/pull/642)

I deleted the following code **without** replacement:

- Computing FUNC parameter size for 32 bit Windows based on argument type information. Now FUNC entries on 32 bit Windows will only have a non-zero parameter size if they can get it from the "C decorated" name of a public symbol at that same address. Otherwise the parameter size will be zero, and stack walking needs to obtain it from the STACK WIN entries. rust-minidump already prefers the size from the STACK WIN entries anyway, because the FUNC parameter size was found to be incorrect in some cases, see #284. Furthermore, all 32 bit dll / exe files which I tested already generated STACK WIN entries for all of their PDB's FUNC addresses.
- Getting "has code" information from section contributions. This was used to include more public symbols, but it didn't seem necessary. The symbolic PDB code doesn't look at section contributions at all, only at the section headers themselves. Checking the section header's "characteristics" seems to work fine and includes all symbols we care about.
- Detecting split functions based on Block symbols with disjoint address ranges.
- Splitting line information based on any encountered disjoint address ranges.
- Splitting line information based on the PDB's address map. For these last three, I haven't found a PDB for which this was necessary.

---

I've done a lot of comparisons of before/after .sym files.

The remaining differences I've found all fall in the following categories:

- Extra leading underscores. I think in the past we were sometimes stripping leading underscores twice, mostly by accident.
- Different (better) demangling, thanks to https://github.com/getsentry/symbolic/pull/640
- Some functions use different names because of a different arbitrary choice between multiple functions at the same address.
- Fewer FILE records, because the cross-platform code omits unused FILE records.
- Different file IDs in line records, as a result of the different FILE records.
- Sometimes fewer line records because duplicate consecutive lines have been merged into one.
- ntdll has more PUBLIC symbols now. I'm not quite sure why but I appreciate it.

title: Don't strip underscores from pdb FUNC names.
body:
When we have a procedure symbol, and then later find a public symbol
at the same address, we try to get the parameter size from the public
symbol's name. But we didn't only got the parameter size, we also
overwrote the function name with the undecorated function name.
This overwriting is not necessary:

 - If the function has a non-zero TypeIndex, we will use the TypeFormatter
   to add parameters, and we want to add those to the original function
   name, not to the undecorated name from the PUBLIC.
 - If the function has a zero TypeIndex, we will call FuncName::get_unknown
   again, and it will get undecorated at that point.

Storing the undecorated name here meant that some functions lost their
leading underscores.

title: Use pdb_addr2line::TypeFormatter
body:
Fixes #279.

This deletes src/windows/types.rs. Small parts of it are moved to symbol.rs, the rest is inside the pdb-addr2line crate.

The output is identical to before, with a few very minor exceptions.

I've tested the following:

 - This 32-bit [xul.dll](https://symbols.mozilla.org/xul.dll/62B4257C68AC000/xul.dl_) / [xul.pdb](https://symbols.mozilla.org/xul.pdb/D41AEBCD66C8379B4C4C44205044422E1/xul.pd_): No difference.
 - This 64-bit [xul.dll](https://symbols.mozilla.org/xul.dll/62B4284C719B000/xul.dl_) / [xul.pdb](https://symbols.mozilla.org/xul.pdb/B2A2B092E45739B84C4C44205044422E1/xul.pd_): One difference, of the good kind.
 - This 64-bit [combase.dll](https://msdl.microsoft.com/download/symbols/combase.dll/9E680117379000/combase.dll) / [combase.pdb](https://msdl.microsoft.com/download/symbols/combase.pdb/071849A7C75FD246A3367704EE1CA85B1/combase.pdb): Four differences, of the bad kind.

The difference in the 64-bit xul.pdb is the following:

```diff
--- xul-pdb.ref.sym     2022-07-03 14:00:44.000000000 -0400
+++ xul-pdb.test.sym    2022-07-03 14:14:11.000000000 -0400
@@ -2031904,5 +2031904,5 @@
 3cd0bd0 40 1342 13929
 3cd0c10 6 1346 13929
-FUNC 3cd0c20 2a7 0 encode_breakout_test(VP9_COMP*, macroblock*, unsigned char, int, int, signed char, unsigned char, unsigned int, unsigned int, buf_2d[1]*, int*, long long*, int*)
+FUNC 3cd0c20 2a7 0 encode_breakout_test(VP9_COMP*, macroblock*, unsigned char, int, int, signed char, unsigned char, unsigned int, unsigned int, buf_2d[3]*, int*, long long*, int*)
 3cd0c20 30 927 13929
 3cd0c50 e 930 13929
```

The `buf_2d[1]*` parameter type has changed to `buf_2d[3]*`. Looking at [the](https://searchfox.org/mozilla-central/rev/dc8033b6b0e45c05ffa8d13415998d9e706a983c/media/libvpx/libvpx/vp9/encoder/vp9_pickmode.c#926) [code](https://searchfox.org/mozilla-central/rev/dc8033b6b0e45c05ffa8d13415998d9e706a983c/media/libvpx/libvpx/vp9/common/vp9_blockd.h#32), it appears that `buf_2d[][3]` would be correct, so both the old and the new behavior seem incorrect. But at least the 3 seems more correct than the 1, even if it's in the wrong place (I think).

In the combase.pdb case, this PR makes us lose a few array sizes - `ArgType[3]&` is replaced by `ArgType[]&` in a few places. This looks like a bug. I'll file it in the pdb-addr2line repo. It seems minor enough that it shouldn't block this PR.

```diff
--- combase.ref.txt     2022-07-04 18:01:49.000000000 -0400
+++ combase.test.txt    2022-07-04 18:00:23.000000000 -0400
@@ -9995,3 +9995,3 @@
 1d175 7 372 1330
-FUNC 1d184 8c 0 FeatureDevelopmentProperties::GetDefaultOverride<enum FeatureDevelopmentProperties::UInt32Property,FeatureDevelopmentProperties::<unnamed-type-g_uint32PropertyDefaultOverrideRecords>,3>(FeatureDevelopmentProperties::UInt32Property, const FeatureDevelopmentProperties::<unnamed-type-g_uint32PropertyDefaultOverrideRecords>[3]&, unsigned int*)
+FUNC 1d184 8c 0 FeatureDevelopmentProperties::GetDefaultOverride<enum FeatureDevelopmentProperties::UInt32Property,FeatureDevelopmentProperties::<unnamed-type-g_uint32PropertyDefaultOverrideRecords>,3>(FeatureDevelopmentProperties::UInt32Property, const FeatureDevelopmentProperties::<unnamed-type-g_uint32PropertyDefaultOverrideRecords>[]&, unsigned int*)
 1d184 2d 826 1331
@@ -42974,3 +42974,3 @@
 9e9d4 d 516 1749
-FUNC 9e9e8 16e 0 FeatureDevelopmentProperties::GetDefaultOverride<enum FeatureDevelopmentProperties::BoolProperty,FeatureDevelopmentProperties::<unnamed-type-g_boolPropertyDefaultOverrideRecords>,2>(FeatureDevelopmentProperties::BoolProperty, const FeatureDevelopmentProperties::<unnamed-type-g_boolPropertyDefaultOverrideRecords>[2]&, bool*)
+FUNC 9e9e8 16e 0 FeatureDevelopmentProperties::GetDefaultOverride<enum FeatureDevelopmentProperties::BoolProperty,FeatureDevelopmentProperties::<unnamed-type-g_boolPropertyDefaultOverrideRecords>,2>(FeatureDevelopmentProperties::BoolProperty, const FeatureDevelopmentProperties::<unnamed-type-g_boolPropertyDefaultOverrideRecords>[]&, bool*)
 9e9e8 2d 826 1331
@@ -86043,3 +86043,3 @@
 1574e6 21 370 1330
-FUNC 157508 fd 0 FeatureDevelopmentProperties::GetDefaultOverride<enum FeatureDevelopmentProperties::UInt32Property,FeatureDevelopmentProperties::<unnamed-type-g_uint32PropertyDefaultOverrideRecords>,3>(FeatureDevelopmentProperties::UInt32Property, const FeatureDevelopmentProperties::<unnamed-type-g_uint32PropertyDefaultOverrideRecords>[3]&, unsigned int*)
+FUNC 157508 fd 0 FeatureDevelopmentProperties::GetDefaultOverride<enum FeatureDevelopmentProperties::UInt32Property,FeatureDevelopmentProperties::<unnamed-type-g_uint32PropertyDefaultOverrideRecords>,3>(FeatureDevelopmentProperties::UInt32Property, const FeatureDevelopmentProperties::<unnamed-type-g_uint32PropertyDefaultOverrideRecords>[]&, unsigned int*)
 157508 a 849 1331
@@ -94542,3 +94542,3 @@
 18b2c5 16 554 1749
-FUNC 18b2dc 3c 0 FeatureDevelopmentProperties::GetDefaultOverride<enum FeatureDevelopmentProperties::BoolProperty,FeatureDevelopmentProperties::<unnamed-type-g_boolPropertyDefaultOverrideRecords>,2>(FeatureDevelopmentProperties::BoolProperty, const FeatureDevelopmentProperties::<unnamed-type-g_boolPropertyDefaultOverrideRecords>[2]&, bool*)
+FUNC 18b2dc 3c 0 FeatureDevelopmentProperties::GetDefaultOverride<enum FeatureDevelopmentProperties::BoolProperty,FeatureDevelopmentProperties::<unnamed-type-g_boolPropertyDefaultOverrideRecords>,2>(FeatureDevelopmentProperties::BoolProperty, const FeatureDevelopmentProperties::<unnamed-type-g_boolPropertyDefaultOverrideRecords>[]&, bool*)
 18b2dc e 896 1331
```

This PR also adds support for correctly resolving cross-module type references. This is why we're threading the module index to various places.
Unfortunately I do not have a PDB file which exercises this code path. All PDBs I've tested have correct function names even if we always specify a module index of zero - including the [crash.pdb in the symbolic repo](https://github.com/getsentry/symbolic/blob/0e4c5bae13fa4fb60a320e51d1a07c26e2464bec/symbolic-testutils/fixtures/windows/crash.pdb), which I know uses cross-module references for some ID indexes (used in inline functions), but since inline functions currently aren't processed by dump_syms, those currently aren't relevant.
But specifying the right module index seems like the right thing to do, so I'm leaving it in.

title: Add support for --inlines for mach-O and ELF
body:
Partially implements #280.

This PR adds a command line argument called `--inlines`. When specified, if dump_syms is run on an ELF or a mach-O file with DWARF information, it now includes "INLINE_ORIGIN" and "INLINE" directives.

I am grouping all INLINE_ORIGIN lines at the start of the file, because that's the most straightforward thing to do with the current setup, because dump_syms currently reads everything into memory first, sorts it, and then emits it. In the future it may make sense to switch to a streaming architecture, for better performance.

There are cases where we're producing slightly incorrect inline information, this is due to https://github.com/getsentry/symbolic/issues/603.

For PDBs, the best plan forward is probably to switch to [`ObjectDebugSession`](https://docs.rs/symbolic-debuginfo/latest/symbolic_debuginfo/enum.ObjectDebugSession.html) for PDBs as well, and just use the same code as for ELF / mach-O. This might require some work in symbolic-debuginfo.

body:
`PathBuf::set_extension` replaces the path's current extension if it already has one, so dump_syms would previously end up writing to e.g. `libc.so.sym` rather than `libc.so.6.sym`.

Closes #384

body: I was a bit too aggressive in #356 and made it so that dumping local symbols didn't work at all, oops!

title: Update dependencies to pick up symbolic version 8.7.3 and the CFI fix for certain x86-64 opcodes
Update dependencies
body:
This updates a few outdated dependencies, but namely `cab` and `simplelog` as the newer version have replaced the unmaintained `chrono` dependency with `time`, which gets rid of two CVEs.

- https://rustsec.org/advisories/RUSTSEC-2020-0159.html
- https://rustsec.org/advisories/RUSTSEC-2020-0071.html

title: Remove inlinee manager
body:
It looks like it wasn't doing anything useful, removing it doesn't change the output on the files I've tested.

`symbolic::debuginfo::Function` has already normalized the line info for us so that all the lines of the outer function describe locations in the outer function. Normalizing was only needed when we were manually using DWARF info, which flattens lines from all levels of the inline nesting into one list. But symbolic already undoes that flattening for us: Lines inside inlined functions are stored on the `Function` for the inline function, not on the `Function` for the outer function. The outer function only has the call location for the inlines in its line info, which is exactly what we need.

If you look at the commits in this PR, the first commit shows that I was trying to deeply understand what InlineeManager does. I concluded that it's not needed for the current output format.

title: Libify
body:
This PR makes changes so that this crate it can be used as a library (eg https://github.com/rust-minidump/minidump-writer/pull/21#discussion_r861912364).

- Replaced `failure` with `anyhow`. `failure` has been [unmaintained](https://rustsec.org/advisories/RUSTSEC-2020-0036.html) for several years, `anyhow` is one of the maintained alternatives. This change is intended as temporary, as IMO the errors in this crate should use `thiserror`, or just manually defined errors, as it makes library usage easier by not using string errors for everything, but made sense for a binary application.
- Places `clap` and `simplelog` behind a `cli` feature flag, these dependencies are only used when used as a binary, crates that depend on this as a library don't need them and thus should not compile them. To preserve backwards compatibility for `cargo install` this feature is made default, so library users will need to explicitly opt-out.
- Places HTTP symbol retrieval behind the `http` feature. This removes several heavy dependencies only used for retrieving symbols from remote symbol stores, in the use case that motivated this PR linked above, this functionality is not needed and only adds compile time for no benefit. Again, this feature is enabled by default for backwards compatibility.
- Replaces `reqwest`'s use of native-tls with `rustls`, simplifying the build when `http` is enabled. I frankly despise OpenSSL and all of the aggravating problems that come with it, `rustls` is a drop-in replacement that completely avoids all of those aggravations. This change is obviously due to my personal bias, I can back it out if requested.

Resolves: #253
